Storage drivers.

The storage driver decides how the image layers and the writable layer are stacked on disk. The default is overlay-two, which uses the kernel's overlay filesystem feature. It is fast, stable, and what almost everyone uses, and it has been the default for years. There are a few alternatives. Two are built on advanced filesystems with native snapshots, well suited to copy-on-write-heavy workloads but requiring docker's data to live on that filesystem, and rarely used outside specific shops. One older option built on the logical volume manager is deprecated and was the default on early red-hat systems. A plain-copy driver makes a full copy of every layer with no copy-on-write, so it is slow and enormous on disk and exists only for testing. And there is a fuse-based overlay used by rootless docker on kernels that lack unprivileged overlay support.

For the overwhelming majority of installs, the right move is to keep overlay-two. You can verify what is active by checking the daemon's reported storage information, where you want to see overlay-two with d-type support enabled, which is the configuration you want.

One serious warning. Switching storage drivers is destructive, because the daemon will not read another driver's existing data. So if you ever do need to change it, you plan it for a maintenance window, with full backups of your images and volumes first, and accept that the existing layer data does not carry over. In practice, the best advice about storage drivers is usually to leave the default alone unless you have a concrete, well-understood reason not to.
